  "prompt": "What is the yield/kiloton of antimatter bomb?",
  "response": "The energy yield of an antimatter bomb can be calculated based on the annihilation of matter and antimatter. When matter (such as protons) meets antimatter (such as antiprotons), they annihilate each other, releasing energy according to Einstein's equation \\(E=mc^2\\).\n\n1 kilogram of antimatter annihilating with 1 kilogram of matter would release approximately \\(9 \\times 10^{16}\\) joules of energy. This is equivalent to about 21.5 kilotons of TNT.\n\nGiven that a practical antimatter bomb would typically use much smaller quantities of antimatter (due to the difficulties in producing and storing it), the yield of such a bomb would depend on the specific design and amount of antimatter used. In theory, even a small amount of antimatter could yield an explosive power significantly greater than conventional weapons. However, actual development and deployment of antimatter weapons remain purely theoretical at this stage.",
